segments.text: And we're testing.
Today is Wednesday, March 4.
And I have the great pleasure and honor of being in Houston in the office of Mayo Thompson, class of 41, chatting with him about his memories of what it was like to be a student at Texas A&M.
Important opening question.
Why did you attend Texas A&M?
Well, the reasons were more than two or three.
First of all, it was at the time in the only school that I thought that I had a reasonable chance to attend because it was at the time a poor boy's school.
In the four years that I was at A&M, starting in September 37,
A room board and laundry never cost more than $30 a month.
That was maintenance.
A matriculation fee was $25 a semester.
And $5.50, as I recall, a semester for medical and athletic past privileges.
So they furnished you a uniform for two years,
Didn't have to worry about buying a lot of clothes.
And so that was one reason.
I had no money, so if I'm going to go someplace, I've got to go where the least of charge is.
And secondly, it was the all-male, all-military environment at A&M at the time appealed to me.
I was active in the ROTC program in the Fort Worth schools.
In junior high school, the highest rank you could get was captain.
I was in junior high school two years, and I did that.
Then I went to Paschal High School, and I was the cadet colonel of the Fort Worth ROTC school, all the high schools in Fort Worth when I graduated.
So it was a natural thing for me, since I had this military bent to me,
to go to A&M.
I liked the idea of the military and of course there was no interruption.
I got out of A&M on the 31st day of May 1941 and didn't go in the army until the next day.
So I was on active duty for five years so I really literally wore a uniform from the time that I was 13 years old to the time I was 26 years old.
Did you visit the campus before you went to enroll?
I'd never been on the campus, not a single time.
I took a midnight chair car out of Fort Worth, and the ticket cost $3.30.
And my mother had no car, so we rode down to the train station in a taxi with my grandmother's old steamer trunk roped on the back of the trunk of the taxi.
And the train left the station at 11.30.
and got into College Station around 5, 5.30 in the morning and stopped a goodly number of times.
And when I got there at the old train station, that was the first time that I had been on that campus.
It was right in the heart of the Depression, of course.
And I had with me my high school transcript, my grandmother's old steamer trunk with all of my belongings in it, and $100 in cash that I had borrowed
from a local businessman in Fort Horton.
I told my mother the night before, I said, well, I'll see you in four years.
But I had not the slightest idea it would not be four days.
But when I got there, they took me in and got me a job.
What was your job?
Well, the first job I had, I worked at the YMCA and then had a job in the
Association office.
And it was summer work that made it possible to make a building of it.
Describe the campus physically when you arrived.
What buildings were there?
What did it look like?
Well, of course there was nothing on the west side of the railroad track.
farmland.
The dairy was over there, as I recall.
Even the vet school was over on the east side.
And Frances Hall, part of Cadet Laura then, was heavy.
Go out and meet Frances Hall and tell us when you met her.
Looking for a person, of course, was a little difficult since it was a building.
The campus was austere, if there was any question about it.
There was no Memorial Student Center.
The YMCA was where you met people if anybody there was to meet.
There was on the campus Aggieland Inn down across from Sabisa and not too far from the post office down at Clark Gate.
They had a few hotel rooms there, and they had a dining room.
And those families that could afford it and came, they would more often than not stay there.
There were no hotels around, at least none that I'm aware of.
And they would stay at A-Land Inn, I must say.
My mother was on the campus one time in four years.
She came down for Mother's Day my senior year.
Incidentally, at the time, we met that day at Kyle Field.
I delivered the Mother's Day address that year.
And I spoke about the coming war in May of 41.
And Dr. T.O.
Walton said that he had heard countless Mother's Day addresses.
He said, I've never heard one where the mothers were told to be prepared for their sons to go to war.
There wasn't much to it.
Highway 6 was a two-lane road.

Freshmen couldn't leave the campus, saved by permission of their units, commanders, and even then, and going home on the weekends was absolutely out of the question until mid-semester when you got your first grades, which you posted on your door.
Hazing was
was very much in vogue in those days.
Describe those events that today would be identified as hazing.
Well, it varied between, there were 54 units on the campus.
There were six regiments.
And those six regiments were divided into 54 batteries, troops, or companies, depending on
which of the combatant branches of the Army that you belonged to.
It was only Army ROTC at the time.
It depended.
It depended.
Each unit varied to some extent.
For example, a freshman was never touched with a board in my outfit.
Never.
And what was your outfit?
I was in G Coast.
Did it have a nickname?
Like later, I would hear about Spider D.
Did you all have a... No.
Okay.
No, not that I recall.
There was a board that was in some use for a long time called Big G. Looked like a canoe pilot.
But go back.
You were about to tell me about the reunion of your unit.
Well, the hazing was the sophomores trained the freshmen.
And they used to wear a room orderly.
Even a sophomore had a room orderly.
Seniors had two.
You went to the post office.
You got the upperclassman's mate.
You got his laundry together.
You ran details for him.
You did everything for him.
A senior could just holler out, freshman, and every freshman that was not in class had to come to the room.
But that was called general fish call.
Others, juniors and sophomores, had to call freshmen by name to get them to come and do something.
You duck walked, you did push-ups.
They aired you out at 11 o'clock at night, made you spend the night in the woods.
They harassed you considerably, cadet lower.
You served the upperclassmen in the mess hall.
You walked in the street.
The freshmen were not good enough to walk on the sidewalk.
And in my outfit, they called sophomores second-year fish.
They didn't think very much of it.
You really didn't begin to enjoy corps life or life at A&M until your junior year.
And then seniors, no matter what their position in the corps was, whether they were the corps commander or a second lieutenant, a senior was a senior was a senior.
And considerable authority vested in them.
We had the first court trip that I went on was when we played Rice in Houston in September, I mean in the fall of 37.
And after we had our parade here.
How did you get down to Houston?
Well, those that could afford it came on a train and the rest of us hitchhiked because there were no cars that were allowed.
Seniors were permitted automobiles and maybe 10 or more seniors in the whole
student body, and they couldn't keep them on campus.
So you got a ride.
In any event, we were, after the parade was over, the sophomores...
Wait, where'd y'all gather?
Where was the parade?
Well, it was down Main Street here in Houston, just like it still is to this day.
You gathered and
Well, I forget now where the assembly point was, but we marched from south to north.
Oh, south to north.
As my recall, and turned on Texas Avenue and went up Travis Street, but I don't remember the exact route of the march.
Then Rice Stadium was at the corner of University and Main, and they had some little ticket booths out there.
There was one man that could sit inside one of those booths.
And when I got out there and other freshmen, there was a massive group.
And some sophomore said, don't worry about the ticket.
We're going to push the fence now.
We're going to go in a big cycle on the fence.
And we're not going to go through the gates.
We're going to push the fence now.
This was some sophomore's idea of a great way to go into the ballgame.
And so the time was set, now I don't remember how long before the game was to start, that we were supposed to push the fence down.
And easily do it, of course.
We used to pick up automobiles in front of the YMCA and move them from the steps when we were getting ready to have Yelp practice.
Put them behind a tree over there.
Had to have a wrecker service come out and get them out.
Whatever.
About five minutes or so, ten minutes before we were just pushed the fence down, a senior
So I can see him to this day standing up there.
He just had boots on.
And in those days, we had whistles.
And they were all chained, and they had them hooked under our blouse pockets on the left.
Whistle-bullet.
And in those days, instead of calling corps attention, it was called battalion attention.
That's the way they did it in the mess.
when they wanted everybody to stop eating except seniors, they would keep eating.
Called the battalion to attention and everything got as quiet as you can imagine with a senior standing up there.
And he said, all right freshmen, all right sophomores, line up.
We're going through the gates.
And he was held down off the top of the little ticket booth.
And we went through the gates.
No fence pushed down.
We went through the gates.
Seniors said, line up, freshmen, line up.
We were going through the gates.
And that was the end of it.
It just shows you the discipline.
There were regular catch-out hitchhiking posts.
And if you got upstream from that, that was a no-no.
And you could drive by there, and if you saw anybody,
that was ahead of the regular catch-out bar.
You just tell them, get your bag, go out to wherever, and they'd pick up their bags and move.
I only saw that two or three times, but I had a senior court in those days.
As you went from Fort Worth to College Station and back, normally where did
Where was the hitchhiking spot?
Okay, it was over on Highway 6 near what is now University Boulevard.
Eastgate?
Eastgate.
Okay.
All right, now where in Fort Worth then?
It was a Catholic school out at the south end of Fort Worth.
I think it was called OLV.
I don't remember Our Lady of Victory, but it was a small girls' Catholic school with commodious grounds, and that's where one stayed in.
So you hitchhiked for four years.
Yeah, I had no car.
And did you or any of your friends ever have any bad experiences hitchhiking?
No.
Did you ever hear of any?
No, never.
No, you had your bag, and in those days they had big A&M stickers.
Everybody just had one on their bag, and you'd go out there.
The problem wasn't getting picked up.
The problem was there weren't any cars.
There was no traffic on that two-lane road.
between Houston and Waco.
Now, with straight face, I ask you this question.
Well, what did you wear when you were hitchhiking?
You wore the same thing you wore on that campus, that uniform, of course.
Let's see.
Tell me, we were on hazing a while ago.
Give me some other details of freshman life routine.
Well, aside from running details for upperclassmen,
And always you kept your door open after call to quarters and before tabs you had to have your door open.
It was true of sophomores as well in my outfit.
And a junior was a hall monitor and you had to be at your desk and look like you're studying or studying.
What were the forbidden dorm room activities?
Well, of course, there wasn't any hell racing in the dormitories at the top.
Could you smoke in your room?
Sure.
Okay.
Sure.
Could you drink alcoholic beverage in your room?
No, that was, I'm not saying it wasn't done, but it was not supposed to be done.
Okay.
Could you?
We weren't supposed to have any on the campus.
Could you have a girl in your room?
No.
I'm not saying it didn't happen, but you were not supposed to.
All right.
What about some of the pranks, jokes, good bull?
Well, the pranks is airing you out and making you spend the night in the woods.
Another is drowning you out.
In the spring and before the summer would come, the campus was littered with mattresses because of the drown-out time.
And where a group would get together and get some buckets and fill them with water.
and you just enter into this room in the dead of night, and while they're in bed asleep, you drown them out.
All right.
Who was normally the victim of a drownout?
Everybody.
Oh, so it wasn't just sophomores?
No, no.
Now, would you ever drown out a senior?
Yes.
Ah.
Yes.
Was it normally within your outfit?
Normally.
Normally.
Can you think of any almost one-of-a-kind pranks, tricks, jokes?
Well, there was fish day on the 1st of April.
In those days, freshmen had white stripes on their left sleeve, as I recall, showing that they were freshmen, because that was the only thing different between them and a sophomore.
The uniforms were the same.
But you take your fish stripe off on the 1st of April,
and you'd go out to Fish Tank, Fish Lake, I forgot what it was called, and you'd usually have a can of beer.
Where was that?
Well, it was out west of the railroad tracks.
I can't remember exactly now where it was.
And you spent the day out there, and it was pretty rowdy.
As a matter of fact, very much so.
But you were then accepted there.
The sophomores quit calling you fish.
You were a month away from being through the semester or two months, April and May, because we didn't usually get out until early June in those days, as you know.
As a freshman, how were you indoctrinated with the routine of being a freshman and whipping out and all that?
How did that come about?
Well, it just was done locally by the sophomores.
In your outfit?
In your outfit.
Alright, you came and what did you think your major was going to be and why?
Well, I'd always wanted to be a lawyer so I took what was then called a pre-law course.
I only had planned to stay at A&M for two years because one could then go over to Austin to go to law school.
And you get a BBA and an LLB in five years.
So that was my intention.
It just so happened that my sophomore year in my outfit, I won the best drill medal, which meant that I was likely to be the first sergeant my junior year, which I was.
So having won that medal, I decided, well, I think I'll just stay.
The fact of the matter is, I had an opportunity to go to West Point.
I got a letter in between my freshman and sophomore year.
I had made earlier indications to my congressman of an interest and I got this announcement that a test was going to be given at a particular place and I didn't even go.
Do you remember what courses you took as a freshman?
Yes, English, chemistry,
from a man to be ultimately the chancellor of A&M.
Yeah, talk about him as a faculty member, teacher.
Well, of course, I guess he taught in those years everybody ever went to him.
I told him, I found me, I got him at a time when he was in a generous mood.
I made a B in freshman chemistry.
His teaching style, what was it like?
Well, of course, big classes.
We had a big amphitheater.
Must have had 250 in the class.
And then you had lab.
So there wasn't anything really close and personal about it.
But was he boring in class?
No, he wasn't.
No.
The subject was boring to me.
I hated chemistry.
I hated it.
Remembering balances or whatever.
H2O was an easy one because it had a two and there was only one and the O had none.
But it was not anything that appealed to me at all.
Did he have a nickname?
I don't remember that he had one.
English, chemistry, what else?
Took algebra.
I'm talking about a liberal arts student now.
Do you remember who?
Oh, I have no idea.
History?
The fact of the matter is, this was my minor.
I majored in economics, a minor in history.
And I had a history course.
And I believe an economics course as well.
Then you took BOLTACS, military science and tactics, which was a one-hour course your freshman and sophomore year.
three hours your junior and senior year.
And it was compulsory for the first two, as you know.
And that consisted of one hour classroom and then three hours drill time, one day a week.
Plus, in those days, everybody carried 18 hours.
I visited with my two
saw raw students, and one of them was taking 12 hours, and the other one was taking 15.
And I said, y'all plan on graduating in five years?
And they said, yes.
That's the norm nationally.
I understand.
And I have a hard time shaking hands with it.
If I told my mother, I said, I'll see you in five years, she would say, well, you're going to do that other year.
And she had a third grade education.
You went to school, and you went for four years.
Mm-hmm.
And I can remember the engineers and those guys taking 21, 22 hours a semester.
I graduated with a surplus of hours.
Not a surplus of grade points, but a surplus of hours.
Yeah, you all did have grade points.
Yeah, we did.
You got three for an A, two for a B, and one for a C, and nothing for a D. Class attendance.
Did you and your classmates go to class regularly?
supposed to, and the reason for it is that if you had three allowable cuts for a three-hour course, if you went beyond that, you got penalized on your grade point.
So you just were self-harmed.
Describe for me, if you can, the routine of a day.
What time did you get up?
What happened during?
If you got up, if you were a freshman, of course, you got up before everybody.
And you went outside and had Yale practice for your outfit.
Then you came back in, you cleaned your own room.
Then you cleaned somebody else's room.
And then you got ready to go to breakfast.
And in those days, we marched to meals.
And you lined up to march at about what time?
Oh, I don't remember.
The classes started at 8 o'clock.
So it was around 7.15, perhaps, something like that.
Who was responsible for waking the group up in your dorm?
The freshmen just took care of one another.
You had nobody else looking after you.
Nobody blew a whistle or anything?
No.
No.
Right then.
All right.
So classes?
Eight to 12 and one to five.
And most of your classes?
And Saturday, eight to 12.
Most of your classes were held in what, where?
Well, where most of my classes were in the academic building and in the old chemistry building.
Well, I took biology as well.
And that was in an old building.
I can't remember the name of it.
Science Hall.
Huh?
Science Hall.
I'll bet.
Well, an old red brick building, as I remember.
Just south of Academic.
Yes.
The president's home is made of those bricks today, turned around.
And let's see.
I'll tell you about Haysing.
It was done clandestinely, this board business.
I can remember my junior year, first sergeant in the outfit.
And something had happened, and I don't know whether the seniors were upset.
Seniors didn't waste their time using the board on the sophomore.
If they used it at all, it was on the junior.
And the juniors on the sophomore, if something wasn't going right.
But I was sitting out, and we were in Mitchell Hall.
We were in Mitchell.
Bazell Goodwin and Hart.
The Coast Artillery Regiment was the third largest regiment on the campus.
So we were all right next to the Y's.
The hospital is there now.
They had steep steps going up, and I was up at the top.
And either Colonel Hill or Colonel Hollinshead came by.
They were the two tactical officers for the Coast Artillery.
Both A&M men.
And you could hear the boards popping.
And of course, when I saw Colonel, I got up and saluted.
And you could hear it.
And he said, well, everything's quiet around here.
Good night, Colonel.
Salute.
I have my senior year in preparation for RV weekend.
I had been appointed by a couple of my classmates when we went across the river in the 14 mile trip and bought some white hard scotch.
And I had it laid out in a drawer that was part of the storage room, the clouded storage facility for the room.
And Colonel Hornshead came in on an inspection.
And he pulled out a drawer in there, which is my senior year.
There was a board line in there, and he closed that, pulled out this next door, and there was whiskey.
He said, well, everything looks neat around here.
On RV initiation, 60 juniors in the company and 60 seniors.
Then there are only 60 seniors, and you don't have 60 juniors.
And you get invited.
And the hazing took place in the horseshoe that Kyle beat.
And senior RVs walk across the campus on a Sunday morning with the boards in their hand.
And you know how that horseshoe is.
A senior here and a senior here.
And you come through and each one of them bangs you three times.
Each junior gets banged six times.
Six times by each of the 60 seniors.
Each junior gets hit six times by these two seniors.
then six, then six, and when you get to the end, you're bloody.
It wasn't near bloody, you were bloody.
You wore one pair of trousers and one pair of shorts, period, paragraph.
And I've seen guys just step over on the side of the line and vomit, get up and get back in the line and finish.
Well, it was terribly, terribly punishing.
But that was just the part, the morning session.
And the afternoon went down to the old rodeo, where they had rodeos, as it calls them, type things.
And there they stripped you down naked.
Are you talking about the pavilion?
The pavilion, whatever it's called.
Right there, near Cushing Library.
Yeah, that's correct.
It used to have some stables along there, where they kept some quarter horses.
And you'd bend down and they'd put wintergreen in the back of your legs, at your knees.
And they dipped raw oysters in asperity and tied string around them.
And you'd lie in there and you'd open your mouth and they'd take it out and you'd swallow it and they'd pull it out.
And then you ran some races and in the meantime you were so sore
Good for you.
Strangest thing, nice.
No, you've got to flip.
You've got to put the lock on.
Now check and see if you can turn it.
No, no, no, no.
Don't put the key in.
It was a grievous, grievous amount of pacing.
It was barbaric.
Now this is all in one day?
All in one day on a Sunday.
In April?
In April.
Then you go back to your outfit and you put on your white uniform.
And you go down to Sabisa Hall for dinner.
And you can't sit.
I was going to say, how did you... Well, you just, and you go to class on Monday and you can't sit.
And of course, when they see you just easing down or
And the professors, of course, know.
And I look back on that.
I've told very few people about it.
Of course, Aggies know about it in my day.
I don't know what they do now, if anything.
It was barbaric.
It was meant to do whatever, and it did.
But those were the outstanding, to be in the RVs, was the cream of the Corps of Cadets crop.
We like to think so.
We like to think so.
